  "text": "[![Avatar](https://shanechang.com/favicon.svg)](https://shanechang.com/)\n# [Shane's Personal Blog](https://shanechang.com/)\n## Gain wisdom at dawn; die with no regret at dusk.\n[](https://github.com/zhangxingeng \"GitHub\")[](https://www.linkedin.com/in/zhangxingeng \"LinkedIn\")[](https://x.com \"x\")[](https://shanechang.com/files/resume.pdf \"Download Resume\")\n  * [Home](https://shanechang.com/)\n  * [About Me](https://shanechang.com/about-me/)\n  * [Portfolio](https://shanechang.com/portfolio/)\n  * [Favorite Quotes](https://shanechang.com/favorite-quotes/)\n  * [Think Different](https://shanechang.com/think-different/)\n\n\nEnglish 简体中文\nDark Mode\n[![Featured image of post Asyncio Best Practices and Common Pitfalls](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/cover_hu_f69855defe0f33ba.webp)](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/)\n[Python ](https://shanechang.com/categories/python/)[Concurrency](https://shanechang.com/categories/concurrency/)\n## [Asyncio Best Practices and Common Pitfalls](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/)\n### Learn the essential best practices and avoid common mistakes when working with Python's asyncio library\nMar 09, 2025\n2 minute read\n[简体中文](https://www.shanechang.com/zh-cn/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/)\nCopy URL Copy as Markdown\n## Table of contents\n6 sections\nTap to expand\n  1. [Writing Better Asyncio Code: Dos and Don’ts](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#writing-better-asyncio-code-dos-and-donts)\n    1. [Best Practices](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#best-practices)\n      1. [1. Use `asyncio.run()` as Your Main Entry Point](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#1-use-asynciorun-as-your-main-entry-point)\n      2. [2. Prefer Async Context Managers](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#2-prefer-async-context-managers)\n      3. [3. Always Await Coroutines](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#3-always-await-coroutines)\n      4. [4. Handle Cancellation Gracefully](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#4-handle-cancellation-gracefully)\n\n\n## Writing Better Asyncio Code: Dos and Don’ts\nPython’s asyncio library is powerful but comes with its own set of conventions and potential pitfalls. Let’s explore the best practices to follow and common mistakes to avoid.\n### Best Practices\n#### 1. Use `asyncio.run()` as Your Main Entry Point\nAlways use `asyncio.run()` to start your asyncio programs:\n\n```\n# Good practice\nasync def main():\n    # Your async code here\n    pass\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    asyncio.run(main())\n\n```\nCopy\nThis function properly sets up and tears down the event loop, and handles cleanup when exceptions occur.\n#### 2. Prefer Async Context Managers\nWhen available, use async context managers (`async with`) for proper resource management:\n\n```\n# Good practice\nasync with aiohttp.ClientSession() as session:\n    async with session.get(url) as response:\n        data = await response.text()\n\n```\nCopy\n#### 3. Always Await Coroutines\nOne of the most common mistakes is forgetting to await coroutines. Always await them:\n\n```\n# Bad - coroutine is created but never executed\nfetch_data(url)\n\n# Good - coroutine is awaited and executed\nawait fetch_data(url)\n\n# Also good - coroutine is executed via asyncio.run()\nasyncio.run(fetch_data(url))\n\n```\nCopy\n#### 4. Handle Cancellation Gracefully\nAlways catch `CancelledError` and clean up resources in tasks that might be cancelled:\n\n```\nasync def cancellable_task():\n    try:\n        # Your task code\n        while True:\n            await asyncio.sleep(1)\n            # Do work...\n    except asyncio.CancelledError:\n        # Clean up resources here\n        print(\"Task was cancelled, cleaning up...\")\n        raise  # Re-raise so caller knows task was cancelle\n\n```\nCopy\n[Asyncio](https://shanechang.com/tags/asyncio/) [Best-Practices](https://shanechang.com/tags/best-practices/) [Debugging](https://shanechang.com/tags/debugging/)All Rights Reserved\n## Related content\nDiscover more articles that might interest you\n[![Featured image of post Asyncio Tasks: Managing Concurrent Operations](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-tasks-explained/cover_hu_4bd96170f57052d5.webp)](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-tasks-explained/)\n[Python ](https://shanechang.com/categories/python/)[Concurrency](https://shanechang.com/categories/concurrency/)\n## [Asyncio Tasks: Managing Concurrent Operations](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-tasks-explained/)\n### Learn how to use asyncio Tasks to run multiple operations concurrently in Python without threads\nMar 09, 2025\n2 minute read\n[![Featured image of post Cooperative Multitasking: The Core of Python Asyncio](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-cooperative-multitasking/cover_hu_32b590788851488c.webp)](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-cooperative-multitasking/)\n[Python ](https://shanechang.com/categories/python/)[Concurrency](https://shanechang.com/categories/concurrency/)\n## [Cooperative Multitasking: The Core of Python Asyncio](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-cooperative-multitasking/)\n### Learn how Python's cooperative multitasking works and how it differs from traditional threading\nMar 09, 2025\n3 minute read\n[![Featured image of post Processing Results as They Arrive with as_completed](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-as-completed-explained/cover_hu_4e22ffeb38d240e1.webp)](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-as-completed-explained/)\n[Python ](https://shanechang.com/categories/python/)[Concurrency](https://shanechang.com/categories/concurrency/)\n## [Processing Results as They Arrive with as_completed](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-as-completed-explained/)\n### Learn how to use asyncio.as_completed to handle task results immediately when they're ready\nMar 09, 2025\n2 minute read\n[![Featured image of post Python Asyncio: Coroutines Explained](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-coroutines-explained/cover_hu_96ed85fd745e5bcb.webp)](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-coroutines-explained/)\n[Python ](https://shanechang.com/categories/python/)[Concurrency](https://shanechang.com/categories/concurrency/)\n## [Python Asyncio: Coroutines Explained](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-coroutines-explained/)\n### A clear explanation of Python coroutines, the fundamental building blocks of asyncio programming\nMar 09, 2025\n2 minute read\n[![Featured image of post Python's GIL and Asyncio: Understanding the Relationship](https://shanechang.com/p/python-gil-asyncio-relationship/cover_hu_9d380b930e8fb9ac.webp)](https://shanechang.com/p/python-gil-asyncio-relationship/)\n[Python ](https://shanechang.com/categories/python/)[Concurrency](https://shanechang.com/categories/concurrency/)\n## [Python's GIL and Asyncio: Understanding the Relationship](https://shanechang.com/p/python-gil-asyncio-relationship/)\n### Learn how Python's Global Interpreter Lock relates to asyncio concurrency and when to use each approach\nMar 09, 2025\n3 minute read\nNickName\nE-Mail\nWebsite\n* * *\n#### Preview:\n[](https://guides.github.com/features/mastering-markdown/ \"Markdown Guide\")\n0  Words\nLoginSubmit\nComments\n  * Latest\n  * Oldest\n  * Hottest\n\n\nPowered by [ Waline ](https://github.com/walinejs/waline) v2.15.8\n© 2022 - 2026 Shane Zhang\nAll Rights Reserved\n## Table of contents\n  1. [Writing Better Asyncio Code: Dos and Don’ts](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#writing-better-asyncio-code-dos-and-donts)\n    1. [Best Practices](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#best-practices)\n      1. [1. Use `asyncio.run()` as Your Main Entry Point](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#1-use-asynciorun-as-your-main-entry-point)\n      2. [2. Prefer Async Context Managers](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#2-prefer-async-context-managers)\n      3. [3. Always Await Coroutines](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#3-always-await-coroutines)\n      4. [4. Handle Cancellation Gracefully](https://shanechang.com/p/python-asyncio-best-practices-pitfalls/#4-handle-cancellation-gracefully)\n\n\n"
